The AP Chemistry exam includes a section of equations and constants that you can reference during the exam. A subset of this reference is shown below.

**Gas equations:**

$\begin{align}
PV &= nRT
\\\\[-1.6em]
P_1 &= P_{\text{total}} \times \chi_1, \text{where}\; \chi_1 = \dfrac{\text{moles of gas 1}}{\text{total moles}}
\\\\[-1.3em]
P_{\text{total}} &= P_1 + P_2 + P_3 + \text{. . .}
\\\\[-0.9em]
\text{K} &= \degree\text{C} + 273
\\\\[-1.5em]
KE\; \text{per molecule} &= \dfrac{1}{2}mv^2
\end{align}$

**Gas variables and constants:**

$\begin{align}
P &= \text{pressure}
\\\\[-1.5em]
V &= \text{volume}
\\\\[-1.5em]
T &= \text{temperature}
\\\\[-1.5em]
n &= \text{number of moles}
\\\\[-1.5em]
m &= \text{mass}
\\\\[-1.5em]
v &= \text{velocity}
\\\\[-1.5em]
R &= \pu{8.314 J mol-1 K-1}
\\\\[-1.5em]
&= \pu{0.08206 L atm mol-1 K-1}
\\\\[-1.5em]
&= \pu{62.36 L Torr mol-1 K-1}
\end{align}$
